Perimeter Defense - Email Security > [T3]: Malicious URLs: A Growing Threat


To bypass strict protection against email attachments, attackers may use a URL in the mail body to deliver the malicious payload. Unlike email attachments, blocking URLs entirely is impossible because it's hard to determine whether a URL is 100% evil. It's somehow a subjective exercise and depends heavily on the context. FireEye noted that there is an increase in URL-based attacks over attachment-based attacks.

 

Figure - zoom in

 

One can easily assume any executable attachment is malicious and block it. On the contrary, a URL can be benign at a specific time and malicious at another time. The attacker can embed a URL that redirects to a legit site, send the email to the victim, and wait a couple of minutes for the mail gateway/sandbox to scan the URL and deliver the mail to the user's inbox. At this point, attackers can easily configure the URL they control to redirect to the malicious site.
 

The difference can be easily seen if we consider attachments as placeholders that carry content inside and URLs as a dynamic pointer to another resource. Lets see examples of how attackers use URLs for their benefit.
